Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of his bed, he put on his combat uniform, put on his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he calmly stepped out of the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. After lighting it, he took a small puff before quietly opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the preset alarm, half the time it didn't work, because everything that came out of the speakers was a faint whistle.
"You're waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Ouep", replied Cohren.
"What have you planned to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith and other soldiers hurried out, already dressed and equipped.
"Hello", said Craith.
"What woke you up?", asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secondly, the first shock troops up are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be".
"You're right, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. An alarm rang out inside the barracks, loud and screeching. He heard commotion inside and some unrest.
"Damn it, Valturi," Nemic shot back. "One would think they would have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my friends from the training camp here did," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their squad and section leaders know how to get up before their units.
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out in mass. Everyone had what they needed, from personal items to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Hello everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"With due respect, sir, why do you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't do sleeping in," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As the first lieutenant and the commander's assistant, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete the final checks and to get rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troops, second army. Originally, they were split into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that had motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the numerous illuminations of the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel attacks, both in the air and on the ground, to fight them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside Ianlos. We've been sent to support the ground assault," replied Cohren while pulling on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, my brother," said Cohren, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're going with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Did Shaw get us a lift?", asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren brought his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone while adjusting his backpack. "To all company units Exodus, rendezvous at the west vehicle park when you are done. We are leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Haris, Craith and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed so long ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith had been commanding the second platoon for a week now, after the previous commander was demobilized, wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy, making sure their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his usually cold face reflecting no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
